---
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="About"
	description="Who's behind groupscout and why it exists"
	pubDate={new Date('2026-03-28')}
>
	<p>
		Hi, I'm Alvin. I'm a software developer based in Vancouver. My wife is a sales manager
		at Sandman Hotel Vancouver Airport in Richmond, BC — and this whole project started because
		I watched her work and thought: <em>there has to be a better way to find these leads.</em>
	</p>

	<p>
		Hotel group sales is a specific kind of grind. You're not waiting for the phone to ring —
		you're supposed to be out there finding business. Construction crews needing a place to
		put 40 workers for six months. Sports teams flying in for a tournament. A film production
		that needs a block of rooms and doesn't care what they cost as long as check-in is smooth.
		That's the job: find them before they find your competitor.
	</p>

	<p>
		The problem is the signals are scattered. Building permits here, contract awards there,
		a news article buried in a Google Alert that nobody has time to read. Piecing it together
		manually is slow and hit-or-miss.
	</p>

	<p>
		So I'm building <a href="https://github.com/alvindcastro/groupscout">groupscout</a> —
		a Go backend that monitors public data sources for exactly these signals, runs them through
		AI enrichment, and delivers a prioritized lead list to Slack every week. No dashboard.
		No login. Just: here are the projects you should be calling about, and here's why.
	</p>

	<p>
		This blog is the story of building it. The technical decisions, the dead ends, the
		"wait, how does hotel sales actually work?" moments, and (fingers crossed) the wins.
		It doubles as a learning exercise — both for me getting better at Go, and for anyone
		curious about using software to solve real-world problems that aren't glamorous but matter.
	</p>

	<p>
		The hotel is real. The problem is real. Let's see if the solution works.
	</p>
</Layout>
